regular medications. She appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She asks about her options for delivery in this pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan for her delivery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Planned caesarean section at 37 weeks","Trial of labour with continuous fetal monitoring","Planned vaginal birth at term","Planned caesarean section at 39 weeks","Induction of labour at 38 weeks"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a history of a previous classical caesarean section, which significantly impacts the management of her current pregnancy. The most appropriate plan is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eplanned caesarean section at 37 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach balances the risks of preterm delivery against the risks of uterine rupture, which increases with advancing gestational age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlanned vaginal birth at term\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for women with a previous classical caesarean section due to the high risk of uterine rupture. The risk of uterine rupture in these cases is estimated to be 4-9%, which is significantly higher than the risk after a lower segment caesarean section (0.5-1%).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etrial of labour with continuous fetal monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E is also not recommended for the same reason. The risk of uterine rupture is too high to justify attempting vaginal birth after a classical caesarean section (VBAC).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlanned caesarean section at 39 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E, while typically the preferred timing for elective caesarean sections in uncomplicated pregnancies, is too late for women with a previous classical caesarean section. The risk of spontaneous labour and uterine rupture before this time is considerable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInduction of labour at 38 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in women with a previous classical caesarean section. Induction would increase the risk of uterine rupture even further.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of pregnancies after a classical caesarean section requires careful planning and counselling. The patient should be informed about the risks of uterine rupture and the reasons for early delivery. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Women with a previous classical caesarean section have a high risk of uterine rupture in subsequent pregnancies.","Planned caesarean section at 37 weeks is the recommended mode of delivery for women with a previous classical caesarean section.","Vaginal birth after classical caesarean section (VBAC) is not recommended due to the high risk of uterine rupture."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Birth after previous caesarean birth. Green-top Guideline No. 45. London: RCOG; 2015. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/media/kpkjwd5h/gtg_45.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39973"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14310"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39973"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-05T08:07:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-05T08:08:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7005"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54464"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags",